br />The direct-IO code really doesn't seem to care at all. I don't think<br />it needs locking either (it seems to do everything with a private<br />buffer-head), and the problem appears solely to be that it reads<br />i_blksize multiple times, so changing it just happens to confuse the<br />direct-io code.<br /><br />If it were to read it only once, and then use that value, it looks<br />like it should all JustWork(tm).<br /><br />And the right thing to do would seem to just add it to the<br />"dio_submit" structure, that we already have. And it already *has* a<br />blkbits field, but that's the "IO blocksize", not the "getblocks<br />blocksize", if I read that mess correctly.<br /><br />Of course, it then *ALREADY* has that "blkfactor" thing, which is the<br />difference between i_blkbits and blktbits, so it effective *does* have<br />i_blkbits already in the dio_submit structure. But despite it all, it<br />keeps re-reading i_blksize.<br /><br />Christ. That code is a mess.<br /><br />              Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
